Ron Müller & Associates (RMA) has conducted this Traffic Impact and Access Study for the
proposed Tri-Valley Commons retail development to be located at 72 Main Street (Route 109),
in Medway, Massachusetts. As proposed, the site will be developed by constructing 22,558
square feet of mixed retail and restaurant space. This includes a 6,800 square foot automotive
parts store Advance Auto Parts), a 6,258 square foot automotive tire store (Goodyear Tire), and
9,500 square feet of additional mixed retail and restaurant space. Access to the site is proposed
via a single full access and egress driveway on Route 109 just east of the Gould’s Plaza shopping
center, opposite the existing Dunkin Donuts exit (easterly) driveway. An internal cross-
connection with Gould’s Plaza is proposed to minimize traffic impacts on Route 109. The site
This report has been prepared to assess the safety of the proposed site driveway, estimate the
increase in traffic as a result of site development, and evaluate the traffic impacts on Route 109
and nearby intersections. Significant roadway improvements are proposed along Route 109 as
part of a Massachusetts Department of Transportation (MassDOT) Route 109 improvement
project. These improvements will include roadway widening, pedestrian and bicycle
accommodations, and improved traffic control from the Main Street/Franklin Street/Milford
Street intersection easterly to the Main Street/Medway Commons/Walgreens driveway
intersection. As this report shows, the development will result in traffic increases on Route 109
ranging from 26 to 70 vehicles during the peak hours. On Holliston Street, the project is
expected to result in traffic increases ranging from 15 to 23 vehicles during the peak hours.
Smaller increases in traffic are expected during all other hour of the day.
With implementation of the MassDOT improvement project, the Route 109 signalized
intersections with Holliston Street and with the Medway Commons/Walgreens driveways are
expected to operate at acceptable levels during the peak hours and the project will have little
impact on traffic operations at these locations. However, long delays are expected for left turns
exiting the site driveway and the other unsignalized driveways in the site vicinity as a result of
eliminating the two-way left-turn lane proposed as part of the Route 109 improvement project.
A safety review of accident incidence in the site vicinity has shown that the number of crashes
along Route 109 from the Medway Shopping Center easterly to the end of the existing center
turn lane are not significant (far less than the statewide average assuming those accidents that
could be attributable to the center turn lane). Accordingly it is recommended that a two-way
left-turn lane be retained in this section of Route 109 as part of the Route 109 improvement
project. Additional roadway widening should be conducted within the existing right-of-way to
allow for construction of a 15-foot wide center turn lane and appropriate signing and striping is
recommended to clearly delineate the use of this lane. With this modification, significant
reductions in delay can be achieved for traffic exiting the many driveways, including the
Based on observed travel speeds, ample sight distance exists at the proposed driveway location
to allow safe operation. It is recommended that sight lines at the new driveway be kept clear of
any obstructions such as landscaping or signs. It is also recommended that the proposed
driveway be constructed to provide two 10-foot wide exiting lanes (for separate left and right
turns) and one 15-foot wide entrance lane. The driveway should provide 30-foot corner radii.
Evaluation of the traffic impacts associated with the proposed site development requires an
evaluation of existing and projected traffic volumes, the volume of traffic expected to be
generated by the project, and the impact that this traffic will have on the adjacent streets and
nearby intersections. In preparing this study, the following intersections were analyzed and
Due to the uses proposed, the development is expected to have little effect on traffic operations
Base traffic conditions within the study area were developed by conducting an automatic traffic
recorder (ATR) counts on Route 109 adjacent to the site to collect weekday and Saturday daily
traffic volumes as well as vehicle speed information. Manual turning movement and vehicle
classification counts (TMCs) were collected at the study area intersections. The TMCs were
performed during the weekday PM peak period (4:00 to 6:00 PM) and the Saturday midday peak
period (11:00 AM to 2:00 PM) to collect peak hour data during times when both the adjacent
street volumes are highest and the development generates the greatest volume of traffic. The
count data indicate that the weekday PM peak hour typically occurs from 4:30 to 5:30 PM and
the Saturday midday peak hour typically occurs from 12:00 to 1:00 PM. All count data were
collected in May 2014 and are provided in the Appendix.
To determine if the count data needed to be adjusted to represent annual average month
conditions consistent with state guidelines for traffic impact assessment, historical traffic volume
data were obtained from MassDOT. The closest permanent count station to the project site is
located on I-495 in Milford at the Medway town line (Station No. 3180). Based on this
information, traffic during the month of May is approximately 3 percent above annual average-
month conditions. Accordingly, the collected data were used without adjustment to represent an
above-average month condition. The MassDOT seasonal adjustment data are provided in the
Appendix and the daily and peak hour traffic flows are summarized in Table 1. The 2014

An intersection accident rate is a measure of the frequency of accidents compared to the volume
of traffic through an intersection and is presented in accidents per million entering vehicles
(acc/mev). For signalized intersections, the statewide average accident rate is 0.80 acc/mev and
the district-wide accident rate is 0.89 acc/mev. For roadway sections, accident rates are
presented in accidents per million vehicles miles traveled (acc/mvm). An urban principal
arterials, which is the classification of Route 109, has a statewide average of 3.23 acc/mvm. A
comparison of the calculated accident rate to the statewide and district-wide averages can be
used to establish the significance of accident occurrence and whether or not potential safety
problems exist. The crash rate worksheets are provided in the Appendix.

As shown in Table 2, the intersection of Route 109 at Holliston Street experienced, on average,
just over 11 accidents per year with a calculated crash rate of 1.04 acc/mev. This rate is higher
than both the statewide and district-wide averages. Significant roadway, signal timing, phasing,
and coordination improvements are proposed as part of the Route 109 improvement project that
are expected to reduce the number of crashes at this location. The intersection of Route 109 at
Medway Commons and Walgreens driveways experienced, on average two accidents per year
with a calculated crash rate of 0.30 acc/mev. This rate is significantly lower than both the
statewide and district-wide averages. Timing and coordination improvements are proposed at
this location as part of the Route 109 state improvement project.
As shown in Table 3, the section of Route 109 between the Medway Shopping Center east
driveway and the end of the existing two-way left-turn lane (at the Metrowest Health Centre at
81 Main Street) experienced, on average, nearly 5 accidents per year with a calculated crash rate
of 3.12 acc/mvm. This rate is lower than the statewide average of 3.23 acc/mvm. A collision
diagram showing the locations and details of these accidents is provided in the Appendix. Based
on the descriptions provided in the actual accident reports, only 5 of the 17 crashes appear to
occurred with vehicle entering or exiting the two-way left-turn lane. These include one vehicle
turning from the center turn lane into a driveway, one sideswipe collisions, one rear-end
collision, and two accidents where vehicles exited a driveway and collided with a vehicle in the
center turn lane. Calculating a crash rate for only those accidents that were directly related to the

MassDOT and the Town of Medway are proposing significant roadway improvements along
Route 109 that include eliminating the existing two-way left-turn lane and replacing it with
exclusive left-turn lanes at selected intersections and driveways. Along the site frontage and
west to the Medway Shopping Center, the plans call for creating an exclusive westbound left-
turn lane. As described in the Mitigation section of this report, an alternate improvement plan is
proposed that would retain the two-way left-turn lane in this section, but widened to 15 feet with
appropriate signing to clearly delineate the lane.

travel time was recorded using automatic traffic recorders and the speed is derived by dividing
the elapsed time into the measured distance between checkpoints. The results of the speed

To identify potential safety concerns associated with site access and egress, sight distances have
been evaluated at the proposed site driveway intersection with Route 109 to determine if the
available sight distances for vehicles exiting the site meet or exceed the minimum distances
required for approaching vehicles to safely stop. The available sight distances were compared
with minimum requirements, as established by the American Association of State Highway and
AASHTO is the national standard by which vehicle sight
distance is calculated, measured, and reported. The MassDOT and the Executive Office of
Energy and Environmental Affairs (EEA) require the use of AASHTO sight distance standards
when preparing traffic impact assessments and studies, as stated in their guidelines for traffic
Sight distance is the length of roadway ahead that is visible to the driver. Stopping Sight
Distance (SSD) is the minimum distance required for a vehicle traveling at a certain speed to
safely stop before reaching a stationary object in its path. The values are based on a driver
perception and reaction time of 2.5 seconds and a braking distance calculated for wet, level
pavements. When the roadway is either on an upgrade or downgrade, grade correction factors are
applied. Stopping sight distance is measured from an eye height of 3.5 feet to an object height of
2 feet above street level, equivalent to the taillight height of a passenger car. The SSD is
measured along the centerline of the traveled way of the major road.
Intersection sight distance (ISD) is provided on minor street approaches to allow the drivers of
stopped vehicles a sufficient view of the major roadway to decide when to enter the major
roadway. By definition, ISD is the minimum distance required for a motorist exiting a minor
street to turn onto the major street, without being overtaken by an approaching vehicle reducing
its speed from the design speed to 70 percent of the design speed. ISD is measured from an eye
height of 3.5 feet to an object height of 3.5 feet above street level. The use of an object height

see another vehicle, then the driver of that vehicle can also see the first vehicle). When the minor

SSD is generally more important as it represents the minimum distance required for safe
stopping while ISD is based only upon acceptable speed reductions to the approaching traffic
stream. However, the ISD must be equal to or greater than the minimum required SSD in order
to provide safe operations at the intersection. In accordance with the AASHTO manual, “If the

to stop or slow to accommodate the maneuver by a minor-road vehicle. To enhance traffic

Future traffic conditions were projected to the year 2021, representing a 7-year design horizon
consistent with EEA and MassDOT requirements for traffic impact analysis. To project traffic
conditions within this design horizon, two components of traffic growth were included. First, an
annual average traffic growth rate was determined to account for general population growth and
smaller development projects (i.e. residential subdivisions) that may impact traffic in the site
vicinity. Based on historical traffic volume information from the MassDOT permanent count
station on I-495 in Milford (Station #3180) at the Medway town line, traffic volumes have
decreased between 2005 and 2009 (the latest years of available data). Comparison of the May
2014 study area counts and previous counts collected in April 2011 at the Route 109
intersections with Holliston Street and with the Medway Commons/Walgreens driveways show a
slight decrease of approximately one percent annual growth. To provide a conservative
analytical framework, a traffic growth rate of one percent per year was used in this study. The
MassDOT historical traffic data are provided in the Appendix.
Second, any planned or approved specific developments in the area that would generate a
significant volume of traffic on study area roadways within the next seven years were
considered. Based on discussions with local officials, there are no development projects in the
area that would add significant traffic above the annual growth rate.
The Town of Medway and the MassDOT Highway Division are proposing the reconstruction of
Main Street (Route 109) in Medway from the its intersection with Franklin Street/Highland
Street in the west to the Medway Commons/Walgreens driveways intersection in the east
(approximately 1.5 miles). The improvement project is currently at the 75 percent design stage
with design plans prepared by Greenman-Pedersen, Inc. (GPI), Copley Wolf Design Group, and
The proposed project includes roadway, striping, and signage improvements, pedestrian and
bicycle accommodations, as well as new traffic signal installation and upgrades of existing
signals. The project also includes elimination of the existing center left-turn lane on Route 109.
In the vicinity of the site, Route 109 will be reconstructed to provide single through lanes in each
direction and a westbound left-turn lane from where the existing center turn lane currently ends
to a new traffic signal proposed at the Medway Shopping Center. At the Route 109 intersection
with Holliston Street, the Route 109 eastbound and westbound approaches will provide an
exclusive left-turn lane, a through lane, and a channelized right-turn lane under Yield control.
The Holliston Street southbound approach will provide an exclusive left-turn lane, a through
lane, and an exclusive right-turn lane. The Holliston Street northbound approach will provide an
exclusive left-turn lane and a shared through/right-turn lane. The traffic signal will be upgraded
and the Route 109 and Holliston Street approaches will operate under fully actuated control with
protected/permissive left-turn phases. An exclusive pedestrian phase and signal coordination
will also be provided with the Route 109 intersection at the Medway Commons and Walgreens
Although no geometric changes are proposed at the Route 109 intersection with Medway
Commons and Walgreens driveways, the traffic signal will be upgraded to provide a fully
actuated control with protected left-turn phases for the Route 109 approaches and concurrent
phases for the Medway Commons and Walgreens driveways. An exclusive pedestrian phase and
signal coordination will also be provided. These traffic control signals will be part of a
coordinated system with the master control at the Route 109 and Holliston Street intersection.
Construction of these improvements will begin in the summer of 2015 with completion expected
prior to the 7-year design horizon and are therefore included under the future No-Build
The 2021 No-Build networks were accordingly developed by applying a compounded 1.0
percent annual growth rate (7.2 percent over seven years) to the existing adjacent street volumes
and by assuming completion of the above planned roadway improvement project. The 2021 No-
Build peak-hour traffic-flow networks are shown on Figure 3.

Not all vehicle trips generated by the project, however, represent new trips. Studies have shown
that retail developments generate a large portion of their business from the traffic already present
on the adjacent roadway. This traffic is referred to as pass-by trips. Based on data published in
the ITE Trip Generation Manual, an average of 28 percent of the tire store, 43 percent of the
automobile parts store, 34 percent of the weekday shopping center, and 26 percent of the
Saturday shopping center total traffic generated is typically pass-by traffic. Therefore, while the
total traffic generated by the project will be realized at the site driveway, the impact of that
traffic on the adjacent streets is substantially less. Table 5 also summarizes the expected volume
of pass-by trips and the resulting new trips to be added to the surrounding roadways.
As shown in Table 6, during the weekday PM peak hour the proposed development project is
expected to add 102 new peak hour vehicle trips to the adjacent streets with the remaining traffic
generated by the project already present in the adjacent traffic stream. During the Saturday peak
hour, 157 new vehicle trips will be added to the surrounding streets.
The distribution of new traffic generated by the project is based on surrounding population
densities, existing traffic volumes, and distribution of traffic at other area retail uses such as
Gould’s Plaza. It is accordingly expected that approximately 45 percent of the new site traffic
will be oriented to/from the west on Route 109, 25 percent to/from the east on Route 109, 15
percent to/from the north on Holliston Street, and 15 percent to/from south on Holliston Street.
Pass-by trips are expected to be drawn from the adjacent street based on the directional
distribution of traffic on Route 109 during the respective peak hours.

generated by the proposed project were assigned to the roadway network as shown on Figure 4

operates at overall acceptable levels (LOS C to D) with all lane groups operating under capacity
(v/c <0.94) during the peak hours. Under the future No-Build and Build conditions, this
intersection was evaluated with the proposed state improvements completed. With these
improvements, the intersection is expected to continue to operate at acceptable levels during the
peak hours (LOS C to D) with slight reductions in delay and volume-to-capacity ratios (max. v/c
The signalized intersection of Route 109 with the Medway Commons and Walgreens driveways
currently operates at an overall LOS B with all lane groups operating under capacity (v/c <0.75)
during the weekday PM and Saturday midday peak hours. Under the future No-Build and Build
conditions, the intersection was evaluated with the proposed state improvements completed.
With these improvements, the intersection is expected to operate at LOS B to C during the peak
hours. The additional traffic from the proposed project will have little impact on the operation of
these signalized intersections under future conditions.
The Gould’s Plaza and Dunkin Donuts driveways currently operate with all turns at LOS D or
better and under capacity. This is due to the fact that left turns exiting these driveways can use
the center turn lane to make a two-step turn and only need to find a gap in traffic in one direction
at a time. However, under the future conditions, the Route 109 improvement project proposes to
eliminate this two-way left-turn lane and replace it with an exclusive left-turn lane in the
westbound direction from the Metrowest Health Centre at 81 Main Street to the new traffic
signal proposed at the Medway Shopping Center driveway. This will require left turns from all
driveways in between to find a gap in traffic in both directions, resulting in LOS F operation
under No-Build and Build conditions. The site driveway approach to Route 109 is also expected
to operate at LOS F with the Route 109 improvement project constructed, with left-turn volumes
exceeding the capacity of the movement. Elimination of the two-way left-turn lane as proposed
will also cause delays for eastbound through traffic whenever traffic has to stop to make a left
turn into Gould’s Plaza or into the proposed Tri-Valley Commons driveway.
As described in the Accidents section of this report, the section of Route 109 from the Metrowest
Health Centre westerly to the Medway Shopping Center east driveway experienced an accident
rate less than the statewide average and the number of crashes directly related to the center turn
lane were minimal (approximately 1.5 accidents per year). Accordingly, it is recommended that
a two-way left-turn lane be retained in this section of Route 109 as part of the Route 109
improvement project. Such a turn lane has the benefit of allowing traffic turning into driveways
a safe place to wait for a gap in traffic without stopping through traffic on Route 109. The two-
way left-turn lane also has the benefit of allowing left turns exiting the many driveways to make
a two-step turn and only needing to find a gap in traffic in one direction at a time.

As described within this report, Route 109 in this section carries approximately 21,300 vehicles
per day and has a high density of driveways (12 curb cuts within approximately 870 feet). A
total of 246 left-turn movements are projected during the Saturday peak hour with the inclusion
of the proposed Tri-Valley Commons project. The Route 109 improvement project will provide
significantly wider shoulders (5-feet) than exist today. It is therefore recommended that
additional roadway widening be conducted within the existing Route 109 right-of-way to allow
for construction of a 15-foot wide center turn lane. Compared with the existing 12-foot wide
center turn lane, this additional width will allow left-turning traffic more comfort to move into
the lane and not block through traffic as frequently occurs today. In addition, appropriate
signing is recommended to clearly delineate the use of this lane, including the provision of
overhead signing at the beginning and end of the proposed center turn lane. Finally, it is
recommended that the proposed two-way left-turn lane be extended further east nearing the
Holliston Street intersection to incorporate the three existing commercial driveways along this
section of road. The two-way left-turn lane can then be transitioned into an exclusive eastbound
left-turn lane onto Holliston Street. The recommended improvements are shown on the
Conceptual Improvement Plan provided at the end of this report.
The analysis results of the Route 109 unsignalized intersections with the Gould’s Plaza
driveway, the Dunkin Donuts driveways, and the proposed site driveway under future No-Build
and Build conditions with a two-way left-turn lane is summarized in Table 8. As shown, the
inclusion of a center turn lane will result in significantly improved operation between the No-
Build and Build “mitigated” conditions. Although some movements will still incur long delays,
all movements will operate well under capacity.
